# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2019-afl-women-s-draft
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2016-afl-women-s-draft] The **2016 AFL Women's draft** consisted of the various periods when the eight clubs in the AFL Women's competition recruited players prior to the competition's inaugural season in 2017.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2016-afl-women-s-draft] Draftees and signings over the period were required to have a minimum age qualification of 18.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2016-afl-women-s-draft] Prior to the draft itself each club was allowed to sign two marquee players from any state across the country at an increased salary.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2016-afl-women-s-draft] In addition, they were permitted to sign a number of priority players with existing connections to the club, and up to two rookie players who had not played competitive Australian rules football within the previous three years.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2016-afl-women-s-draft] All remaining players entered the draft and became eligible to be selected by any team based in their nominated state-based zone.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2016-afl-women-s-draft] On 27 July 2016, each of the competition's eight teams announced their two marquee player signings allowed prior to the October draft.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2016-afl-women-s-draft] Under the priority selection rules, Carlton, Collingwood, Melbourne, the Western Bulldogs and Fremantle were allowed one player, Adelaide and Brisbane were allowed two players, and Greater Western Sydney was allowed four.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2016-afl-women-s-draft] Due to injuries to their marquee players, Fremantle and Greater Western Sydney were permitted an additional priority pick, allowing for two and five in total, respectively.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2016-afl-women-s-draft] A state based draft was held on 12 October 2016.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2016-afl-women-s-draft] The draft order was determined by random draw on 29 September.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2016-afl-women-s-draft] The draft operated in snake formation with the club holding the first selection of the first round also holding the last selection of the second round and so on and so forth.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2016-afl-women-s-draft] Each team had until 31 October 2016 to sign further undrafted/free-agent players to complete their list of 25 senior listed players.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-draft] The **2017 AFL Women's draft** consisted of the various periods when the eight clubs in the AFL Women's competition could recruit players prior to the competition's 2018 season.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-draft] As the previous season's player contracts were all capped at one-year deals, all existing AFLW players must be re-signed prior to the 2018 season.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-draft] Entering the second season of the competition, clubs will have larger list sizes, with 27 senior listed players (up from 25), and three rookie listed players (up from two).
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-draft] Beginning 1 May, clubs were given an 18-day window to re-sign players on their lists from the previous season, with teams being required to retain between 15 and 22 players during that period.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-draft] There was also a window for teams to trade players and draft picks in a trade period that started on 15 May 2017, and continued for 12 days.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-draft] Players were eligible to seek a trade should they receive a contract offer from a rival club at a pay scale level above their previous years' salary.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-draft] Players could also reject any offer from their existing club lower rate than in 2017, and become restricted free agents permitted to sign with another club at or above their previous salary.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-draft] Players who do not receive offers from their 2017 club were free to sign with any club during the four-day free agency period starting 29 May 2017 or to nominate for the 2017 draft.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-draft] A four-day free agency period was held from 29 May for clubs to secure non-signed players from other clubs.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-draft] A second free agency period opened at the conclusion of the draft, allowing undrafted players to be signed.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-draft] This period closed on 19 October, the day after the draft.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-draft] AFLW players salaries are managed and paid in full by the AFL on behalf of the clubs.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-draft] It is expected that these salaries will be renegotiated and increased, as the time commitment of players was found to be greater than expected during the 2017 season.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-draft] In addition, players are provided with playing boots and runners, an interstate travel allowance, income insurance, out-of-pocket medical expense coverage, and an allowance to pay for a carer for a child under 12 months of age when travelling interstate.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-draft] It operated with players nominating for a single state's draft pool and players only being eligible to be drafted by clubs operating in that state.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-draft] Clubs concluded the draft period with a total of 30 players, 27 of these being senior listed and three of these being rookie players.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-draft] The rookie draft took place on 20 October 2017.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-draft] Players qualify for the rookie draft if they are under the age of 21 or are crossing from another sport.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2018-afl-women-s-draft] The **2018 AFL Women's (AFLW) draft** consisted of the various periods when the ten clubs in the Australian rules football women's competition could recruit players prior to the competition's 2019 season.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2018-afl-women-s-draft] As in the previous season, all player contracts are all capped at one-year deals, and all existing AFLW players must be re-signed prior to the 2019 season.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2018-afl-women-s-draft] For the 2019 season, the league and the AFLPA agreed to the AFLW's first collective bargaining agreement (CBA).
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2018-afl-women-s-draft] From 11 May expansion clubs Geelong and North Melbourne were given a ten-day window to sign existing players from 2018 AFLW lists.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2018-afl-women-s-draft] These clubs could sign a maximum of four players between them from any existing club.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2018-afl-women-s-draft] No compensation was offered to those clubs losing players under this process, but the each player's existing club could make a counter-offer to the player.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2018-afl-women-s-draft] A number of deals were agreed to in principle and acknowledged by clubs prior to the opening of this window.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2018-afl-women-s-draft] Beginning 23 May, clubs were given a 13-day window to re-sign players on their lists from the previous season During this time clubs were also permitted to arrange player and pick trades with other clubs.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2018-afl-women-s-draft] Players who do not receive offers from their 2017 club will be free to sign with any club during the four-day free agency period starting 4 June or to nominate for the 2018 draft.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2018-afl-women-s-draft] A four-day free agency period was held from 4 June for clubs to secure non-signed players from other clubs.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2018-afl-women-s-draft] A second free agency period is expected to be opened at the conclusion of the draft, allowing un-drafted players to be signed.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2018-afl-women-s-draft] Following final list lodgements, a number of players experienced changing circumstances that made them unable to participate in the 2019 season.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2018-afl-women-s-draft] Clubs were granted permission to place these players on an inactive list, retaining rights to their services at a assigned cost in the 2019 draft while replacing them for the one season.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2018-afl-women-s-draft] In some cases, compensation was awarded in pre-draft listing at the cost of a discounted draft selection.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2018-afl-women-s-draft] A draft was held at Melbourne's Marvel Stadium on 23 October 2018.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2018-afl-women-s-draft] As in previous drafts, players nominated a single state's draft pool, and players are eligible to be drafted only by clubs operating in their nominated state.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2018-afl-women-s-draft] In addition, Victorian players could nominate for one of three Victorian zones: Geelong, Melbourne metro, or the entire state.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2018-afl-women-s-draft] A final free agency period opened after the conclusion of the draft, allowing clubs that passed on a draft selection to recruit from outside their state-based zone.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-all-australian-team] The **2019 AFL Women's All-Australian team** represents the best-performed players of the 2019 AFL Women's season.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-all-australian-team] It was announced on 2 April 2019 as a complete women's Australian rules football team of 21 players.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-all-australian-team] The team is honorary and does not play any games.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-all-australian-team] The initial 40-woman All-Australian squad was announced on 21 March.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-all-australian-team] Adelaide had the most players selected in the initial squad with nine, and every team had at least two representatives.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-all-australian-team] Nine players from the 2018 team were among those selected.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-all-australian-team] The final team was announced on 2 April.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-all-australian-team] Premiers Adelaide had the most selections with five, and every team except Greater Western Sydney had at least one representative.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-all-australian-team] Four players from the 2018 team were selected, three of whom – Adelaide co-captain Chelsea Randall, Melbourne's Karen Paxman and North Melbourne captain Emma Kearney – achieved selection for the third consecutive year.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-all-australian-team] Adelaide's other co-captain, Erin Phillips, was announced as the All-Australian captain and Randall, the previous year's All-Australian captain, was announced as the vice-captain.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-all-australian-team] Note: the position of coach in the AFL Women's All-Australian team is traditionally awarded to the coach of the premiership-winning team.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-best-and-fairest] The **2019 AFL Women's best and fairest** was the award presented to the player adjudged the best and fairest player during the 2019 AFL Women's season.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-best-and-fairest] Erin Phillips of the Adelaide Football Club won the award for the second time, winning with 19 votes.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-best-and-fairest] The three field umpires (the umpires who control the flow of the game, as opposed to goal or boundary umpires) confer after each match and award three votes, two votes and one vote to the players they regard as the best, second-best and third-best in the match, respectively.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-best-and-fairest] The votes are kept secret until the awards night, and are read and tallied on the evening.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-draft] The **2019 AFL Women's draft** consisted of the various periods when the 14 clubs in the AFL Women's competition can recruit players prior to the competition's 2020 season.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-draft] At the conclusion of the period clubs were required to have 27 senior-listed and three rookie-listed players.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-draft] Prior to the completion of the 2019 season, future expansion clubs Gold Coast, Richmond, St Kilda and West Coast were permitted to pre-list up to 10 players from their women's academies or designated development zones.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-draft] A maximum of seven of these players could be open-age signings who had nominated for the 2018 AFL Women's draft but not been selected.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-draft] A final three spots were reserved for three junior players of minimum draft age (born in 2001) and who hailed from the clubs' designated development regions.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-draft] From 8 April expansion clubs Gold Coast, Richmond, St Kilda and West Coast will have an 11-day window until 18 April to sign players who played for existing clubs during the 2019 season.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-draft] These clubs can sign a maximum of 12 players each through this mechanism.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-draft] All existing clubs other than Brisbane and Fremantle could lose no more than four players to the mechanism while Brisbane and Fremantle can each lose a maximum of eight due to the entry of Gold Coast and West Coast into their previously exclusive state-zones.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-draft] No compensation will be offered to those clubs losing players under this process, but the player's existing club are permitted to negotiate to re-sign the player.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-draft] Players can be signed under this mechanism to one or two year contracts.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-draft] Concurrently to the expansion club signing period, all 14 clubs were able to sign and trade players.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-draft] Players can be signed during this period are eligible for one or two year contracts.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-draft] A second stage to the trade period will open from 23 April and run until 26 April, with only the 10 established clubs able to take part.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-draft] A free agency period was held between the end of the trading and signing period on April 26 and until April 30 in which clubs were permitted to sign delisted or uncontracted players.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-draft] At the conclusion of the period, clubs are permitted to have retained no more than 22 senior players and two rookies.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-draft] Team lists matching those requirements must be submitted on May 3.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-draft] In the absence of a rookie draft, each club was required to sign two rookie players, either new or retained from their rookie list the year prior.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-draft] New players to this list must not have played Australian rules football within the previous three years or been involved in an AFLW high-performance program.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-draft] Players nominated for a single selection pool, aligned to a state or metropolitan region, with players only being eligible to be drafted by clubs operating in that region.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-draft] An indicative draft order was published in early April while the final draft order was published by the AFL in the wake of the expansion signing period on 23 April.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-draft] Before the opening round of the season, clubs were permitted to replace players who had suffered a long-term injury or for whom personal circumstances had ruled them out for playing in any match that year.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-draft] The replacement players are signed to a train-on list and are considered semi-eligible for section.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-draft] Though they are eligible to train with the club, they cannot be selected for match play until further injuries to player on the club's list mean a club has fewer than 23 players available for any single match.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-draft] was given special permission to treat Saad as a full signing.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] The **2019 AFL Women's Grand Final** was an Australian rules football match held at Adelaide Oval on 31 March 2019 to determine the premiers of the league's third season.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] Admission was free to the general public, and the match between Adelaide and Carlton was contested before a crowd of 53,034 – which at that time was the record for a stand-alone women's sporting event in Australia.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] It was won by Adelaide, 10.3 (63) to 2.6 (18), and Adelaide claimed its second premiership in three years.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] Its co-captain Erin Phillips was voted best on ground, despite suffering an anterior cruciate ligament (ACL) injury in the third quarter.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] Two new teams, Geelong and North Melbourne, joined the AFL Women's (AFLW) competition in 2019, bringing the total number of teams to ten.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] The league retained a seven-round home-and-away season.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] This was achieved by splitting the competition into two conferences, with one of the new teams in each.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] Each team played four games against their fellow conference members and three "cross-over" matches against teams from the other conference.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] Conference membership was based on the final ladder positions of the 2018 season.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] As it turned out, the competition was unbalanced, with Conference A teams winning 14 of the 16 cross-over matches.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] The finals series was expanded to include preliminary finals for the first time.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] The two teams that finished the highest in each conference at the end of the home-and-away season qualified for the preliminary finals, with the team that finished highest in Conference A playing the team that finished second in Conference B and vice versa.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] The winners of these matches then played in the AFL Women's Grand Final.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] After winning the 2017 AFL Women's Grand Final, the Adelaide Crows finished a disappointing fifth in 2018.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] The Carlton Blues, which were also expected to perform well in 2018, did much worse, ultimately battling Fremantle for the wooden spoon – and getting it.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] In 2019, both Adelaide and Carlton had new coaches – Matthew Clarke and Daniel Harford respectively.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] The Crows retained much of their team from 2017 and 2018, but lacked a ruckman after Rhiannon Metcalfe was sidelined for an ACL reconstruction and Jasmyn Hewett suffered an ankle injury.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] Former Opals basketball player Jess Foley was pressed into the ruck role at the last minute.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] The Crows went on to an impressive season, notching up seven games by an average of 40 points, and finishing on top of Conference A.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] Their only loss for the season was by a single point in the first round match against the Western Bulldogs, when they kicked an inaccurate 1.11.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] Carlton got off to a slow start, losing to North Melbourne in round one and then Adelaide in round two, before winning five of the last six games to finish on top of Conference B.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] In their preliminary final, the Crows conducted a 66-point demolition of Geelong before a home crowd of 13,429 at the Adelaide Oval, not allowing the visitors to score until late in the final quarter.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] The conference system ensured that Carlton, which finished at the top of Conference B, also hosted the preliminary finals.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] This was seen as disadvantaging Fremantle, which had won two more games than Carlton, and had a far better percentage (141.2 per cent compared with 99.6 per cent).
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] In the lead up to the preliminary final, an image of Carlton's star forward Tayla Harris demonstrating her on-field athleticism that was posted online by the Seven Network came under attack by misogynist internet trolls.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] Rather than suppressing their comments, Seven took the image down, resulting in a chorus of outrage.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] In the preliminary final, Harris went on to demonstrate her kicking style, slotting Carlton's first goal from 45 metres out.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] The Blues went on to win by 36 points, setting up a grand final clash with Adelaide.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] As the highest-ranked team across the two conferences, Adelaide won the right to host the grand final.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] The match was scheduled for Sunday, 31 March 2019 at Adelaide Oval, which AFLW Chief Executive Nicole Livingstone conceding this timeslot would clash with a men's game between North Melbourne and the Brisbane Lions.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] Admission was free to the general public, and the AFL hoped for a crowd of around 25,000.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] In the event, the crowd of 53,034 was the largest ever for an AFLW match, the fifth highest ever at Adelaide Oval, and a record for a stand-alone women's sporting event in Australia, surpassing a record set in 1920.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] Extra seating was hurriedly opened in the upper grandstands.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] The unanticipated large crowd put the city's public transport under strain.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] Its record as the highest women's sports crowd in Australian history was surpassed in March 2020 by the 2020 ICC Women's T20 World Cup Final, but as of 2020 retains the record for highest crowd at a women's football match.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] The Blues started well, with Maddy Prespakis scoring an early first goal off a 50-metre penalty on Adelaide co-captain Erin Phillips.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] The Crows were quick to respond with quick ball movement in the centre square from Foley to Ebony Marinoff to Anne Hatchard, who notched up their first score.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] A second 50-metre penalty gave Carlton another chance but was rushed through by Adelaide for a behind by Sarah Allan.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] The Crows were soon back on the attack, with Phillips marking just inside the 50-metre arc.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] Her kick fell short, but Irish recruit Ailish Considine put it through for a second goal.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] A third soon followed with Eloise Jones passing the ball to Hannah Martin for a goal from point-blank range.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] An attempt at the other end by Sarah Hosking resulted only in a behind, and yet another 50-metre penalty gave the Blues an opportunity on the siren, but the ball fell well short of the goal line.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] At quarter time, Carlton felt they were dominating everywhere but on the scoreboard, but this feeling would soon pass.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] The second quarter opened with an Adelaide goal.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] An overhead mark in the centre by Jones was handed off to Phillips, who booted it forward to the advantage of Stevie-Lee Thompson, who marked it and sprinted towards the goal line.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] Thompson proved too fast for the Carlton defenders, who were caught too far out from goal, and a goal resulted.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] A couple of minutes later, Phillips earned a free kick from a high tackle by Sarah Hosking.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] One accurate kick later, and Phillips had ten goals for the season, and Adelaide, five for the match.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] A mark by Renee Forth off a delivery from Deni Varnhagen nearly made it six, but she missed, scoring only a behind.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] The next opportunity came a few minutes later.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] A Carlton turnover saw Allan boot the ball forward to Chloe Scheer, who took a specky over the top of Blues defender Kerryn Harrington.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] She played on and delivered it to Danielle Ponter for an easy first goal.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] Soon after though, Scheer went down with a suspected anterior cruciate ligament injury, and was out of the game.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] It did not halt Adelaide, as Ponter marked a delivery from Jones inside the goal square for her second.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] A third followed, bringing her to twelve for the season.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] Tayla Harris attempted to score one against the flow of play, but it was touched on the line by Allan.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] It fell to Carlton captain Bri Davey to put the Blues' second goal on the scoreboard.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] Jones had a free kick at goal after the siren that sailed through, and Adelaide took a forty-point lead into the half time break.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] When play resumed after the long break, Harris started in the ruck, possibly in an attempt to get her into the game.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] This backfired, as she immediately collided with Davey, and went off clutching her knee.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] Thompson also hobbled off the ground, with an ankle injury.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] Both would return, but not for some time.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] Phillips marked a pass from Forth 40 metres out, and had her second goal of the match.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] Soon after, Phillips went down, clutching her knee, and had to be stretchered off the ground.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] The crowd gave her a standing ovation, and even the Carlton players looked upset.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] In the final quarter, the players had less to show for their efforts.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] Foley missed a shot from 35 metres out, scoring only a behind, as did Chloe Dalton at the other end.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] Hosking was awarded a free kick after being crunched in a tackle by Foley, but missed everything.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] A final effort by the Crows could not score before the final siren sounded.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] Phillips's injury cast a pall over the Crows' win.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] "It's an ACL," she confirmed, "something I have done before in my other leg.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] This was supposed to be the good leg." Despite only playing for three-quarters, Phillips, who had 18 disposals and two goals, was named best on ground, as she had been when Adelaide previously won the flag in 2017.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] The following night she won the AFLW Players' Association's Most Valuable Player award, which she had also previously won in 2017.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] On 2 April, she was awarded the AFLW best and fairest award for second time, having previously won it in 2017, and was named the captain of the 2019 AFL Women's All-Australian team.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] Her Adelaide co-captain Chelsea Randall was named the vice captain, and Hatchard, Thompson and Marinoff were also part of the squad, as were Carlton's Prespakis, Harrington and Gab Pound.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] The game was broadcast live on Channel Seven, Fox Footy, *womens.afl* and the AFLW Official App.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] ARIA Award winner Amy Shark performed songs from her debut album *Love Monster*.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] She said that the Tayla Harris photo incident made her more determined to perform, saying that "[J]ust being a female in music, I'll do anything I can to help highlight any other woman trying to make it in the professional world, no matter what that field is".
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-grand-final] The match was watched live by a television audience of 409,000.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-rising-star] The **2019 NAB AFL Women's Rising Star** award was presented to the player adjudged the best young player during the 2019 AFL Women's season.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-rising-star] Maddy Prespakis of the Carlton Football Club won the award with 49 votes.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-rising-star] Every round, two nominations were given to standout young players who performed well during that particular round.
[src:2019-afl-women-s-draft/2019-afl-women-s-rising-star] To be eligible for nomination, players must have been under 21 years of age on 1 January 2019, not have been suspended during the season and never previously been nominated.
